Photocatalysis of catalysts can be confirmed by measuring the photocurrent generated by the catalyst in the presence of light. Photocurrent of the catalysts Nano-MoS2 and Nano-CD-MoS2 was studied by constructing a custom-made water photolysis system (Fig. 12
                              ). A glass beaker with 80 ml water with pH 7 was used as an electrolyte. A steel rod (length: 3 cm, radius: 3 mm) as anode and a lead rod (length 3 cm, radius: 0.5 mm) as cathode were used to measure the external current. The current flowing between the anode and the cathode was measured using a multimeter. 5 mg of catalyst was added to the electrolyte (concentration: 0.0625 g/L), and photocurrent measurements were taken (Fig. 12a) at noon time. No other external potential was applied to produce current. Table 1
                               shows photocurrent measurements. The more photocatalytic Nano-MoS2 has exhibited a maximum current of 141 µA. A maximum of 120 µA current is recorded for Nano-CD-MoS2. In the presence of light, active edge electrons present in the Nano-MoS2 can easily detach from the site and participate in water photolysis. As explained in PL study, separated electrons and holes in Nano-MoS2 can move more distance through the electrolyte before recombination. In between the separation and recombination, free charges can participate in water splitting.
